== Incidents == * On January 11, personnel from [[Millennium Pipeline]] noticed that a gas transmission pipeline was leaking in [[Tioga County, New York]]. This 30-inch diameter pipeline was built in 2008. A pinhole in a rejected girth weld was found to be the cause of the failure. It appears that during the course of the construction project for the line, the subject pipe section was inadvertently picked up and subsequently installed in the pipeline. PHMSA ordered testing of this pipeline for similar flaws.<ref>{{cite web|title=CPF 1-2011-1013S |url=http://primis.phmsa.dot.gov/comm/reports/enforce/documents/120111013S/120111013S_NOPSO_07062011.pdf |accessdate=28 November 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161225071520/http://primis.phmsa.dot.gov/comm/reports/enforce/documents/120111013S/120111013S_NOPSO_07062011.pdf |archivedate=December 25, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Failure Investigation Report – Columbia Gas Transmission, Millennium Pipeline Weld Anomaly Failure Date 01/11/2011 |url=http://www.phmsa.dot.gov/staticfiles//PHMSA/PipelineFailureReports/CGT_2616_Millennium_West_NY_09132012_[Redacted_for_Internet].pdf |accessdate=28 November 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170127033252/http://phmsa.dot.gov/staticfiles/PHMSA/PipelineFailureReports/CGT_2616_Millennium_West_NY_09132012_%5BRedacted_for_Internet%5D.pdf |archivedate=January 27, 2017 }}</ref> * A 12-inch cast iron gas main leaking in [[Philadelphia]] exploded, killing a repair crew member and injuring six others on January 18.<ref>{{cite web |title=2nd UPDATE: Philadelphia Gas-Line Blast Kills One, Hurts Six |url=https://online.wsj.com/article/BT-CO-20110119-716460.html |accessdate=October 30, 2016 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110123003654/http://online.wsj.com/article/BT-CO-20110119-716460.html |archivedate=January 23, 2011}}</ref><ref name="opsweb.phmsa.dot.gov">{{cite web|url=http://opsweb.phmsa.dot.gov/cast_iron/ |title=Page has moved |publisher= |accessdate=January 15, 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150310100120/http://opsweb.phmsa.dot.gov/cast_iron/ |archivedate=March 10, 2015 }}</ref> * Multiple gas pressure regulators failed, and caused a gas pressure surge in [[Fairport Harbor, Ohio]], on January 24, causing gas fires in 11 houses, and one apartment. 150 gas appliances were damaged or destroyed, but there were no injuries. Gas company Dominion East Ohio says it found fluids and debris in a failed regulator. A year after the explosion, the Public Utilities Commission of Ohio recommended a $500,000 fine for Dominion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news-herald.com/articles/2011/02/02/news/nh3594036.txt?viewmode=fullstory |title=Fairport Harbor blasts probed |publisher=news-herald.com |date=February 2, 2011 |accessdate=April 2, 2013 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313003640/http://news-herald.com/articles/2011/02/02/news/nh3594036.txt?viewmode=fullstory |archivedate=March 13, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|agency=Associated Press |url=http://www.newsnet5.com/dpp/news/local_news/lawsuit-filed-over-natural-gas-fires-in-fairport-harbor |title=Lawsuit filed over natural gas fires in Fairport Harbor |publisher=Newsnet5.com |date= |accessdate=April 2, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309144633/http://www.newsnet5.com/dpp/news/local_news/lawsuit-filed-over-natural-gas-fires-in-fairport-harbor |archivedate=March 9, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news-herald.com/articles/2011/10/19/news/nh4642830.txt |title=Dominion officials respond to Fairport residents |publisher=news-herald.com |date=October 19, 2011 |accessdate=April 2, 2013 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120529082946/http://news-herald.com/articles/2011/10/19/news/nh4642830.txt |archivedate=May 29, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Puco Staff Report Fire Investigation |url=http://www.fox8.com/news/wjw-news-puco-staff-report-fire-investigation,0,910014.story |accessdate=May 14, 2012}}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> * Five people were killed, and eight houses were destroyed, in a gas explosion and fire in [[Allentown, Pennsylvania]] on February 9. The NTSB had warned UGI about cast iron gas mains needing replacement after the 1990 gas explosion in that city. Between 1976 and the date of the letter, July 10, 1992, two more gas explosions occurred. Three people were killed, 23 injured and 11 houses were destroyed or damaged in those explosions. UGI was cited in 2012 for several safety violations, including a lack of valves on their gas system.<ref>{{cite web |title=Five Killed in Pennsylvania Gas Explosion |url=http://www.firehouse.com/news/top-headlines/five-killed-massive-pennsylvania-gas-explosion |accessdate=October 30, 2016 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110221080733/http://www.firehouse.com/news/top-headlines/five-killed-massive-pennsylvania-gas-explosion |archivedate=February 21, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=UGI told years ago to remove old pipes |url=http://www.mcall.com/news/local/allentown/mc-allentown-ntsb-blast-20110301,0,3589679.story |accessdate=October 30, 2016 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121002151407/http://www.mcall.com/news/local/allentown/mc-allentown-ntsb-blast-20110301%2C0%2C3589679.story |archivedate=October 2, 2012 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uG8m7V0KXbs&feature=player_embedded |title=Allentown Explosion |date=February 10, 2011 |publisher= |accessdate=January 19, 2016 |via=YouTube |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203115900/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uG8m7V0KXbs&feature=player_embedded |archivedate=February 3, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wfmz.com/news/news-regional-lehighvalley/UGI-cited-for-multiple-safety-violations-leading-to-Allentown-gas-explosion/-/132502/14773532/-/t2eat7/-/index.html |title=UGI cited for multiple safety violations leading to Allentown gas explosion &#124; Regional: Lehigh Valley – Home |publisher=Wfmz.com |date=June 11, 2012 |accessdate=April 2, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130320172323/http://www.wfmz.com/news/news-regional-lehighvalley/UGI-cited-for-multiple-safety-violations-leading-to-Allentown-gas-explosion/-/132502/14773532/-/t2eat7/-/index.html |archivedate=March 20, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> * Late on February 10, a [[Tennessee Gas Pipeline]] 36-inch gas transmission pipeline exploded and burned near [[Lisbon, Ohio]]. No injuries resulted. The cause was from stress on a girth weld on the pipeline. A failure on another girth weld on the pipeline system led to a PHMSA Consent Agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wytv.com/mostpopular/story/Huge-Natural-Gas-Explosion-Near-Lisbon/P5r50OZ9VkOqkl_ZuNTL0A.cspx |title=Huge Natural Gas Explosion Near Lisbon – 33 News – We Believe in This Valley |publisher=Wytv.com |date= |accessdate=April 2, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325055104/http://www.wytv.com/mostpopular/story/Huge-Natural-Gas-Explosion-Near-Lisbon/P5r50OZ9VkOqkl_ZuNTL0A.cspx |archivedate=March 25, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wfmj.com/story/15677053/cause-of-explosion-in-hanover-township-determined |title=Cause of explosion in Hanover Township determined – 21 News Now, More Local News for Youngstown, Ohio |publisher=Wfmj.com |date= |accessdate=April 2, 2013 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131028060153/http://www.wfmj.com/story/15677053/cause-of-explosion-in-hanover-township-determined |archivedate=October 28, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=CPF No. 3-2011-1001S |url=http://primis.phmsa.dot.gov/comm/reports/enforce/documents/320111001S/320111001S_Consent%20Agreement_03312011.pdf |accessdate=28 November 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170209065759/https://primis.phmsa.dot.gov/comm/reports/enforce/documents/320111001S/320111001S_Consent%20Agreement_03312011.pdf |archivedate=February 9, 2017 }}</ref> * Early on February 24, a pipeline near [[Texas City, Texas]] ruptured, sending up to {{convert|5,000|USgal|L}} of gasoline into Bayou Pierre.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ruptured line held 250,000 gallons of gasoline |url=http://galvestondailynews.com/story/214010 |accessdate=October 30, 2016 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323094518/http://galvestondailynews.com/story/214010 |archivedate=March 23, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=About 5,000 gallons of fuel spilled, TCEQ says |url=http://galvestondailynews.com/story/214398 |accessdate=October 30, 2016 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323094933/http://galvestondailynews.com/story/214398 |archivedate=March 23, 2012}}</ref> * On March 1, a [[Tennessee Gas Pipeline]] gas transmission pipeline failed near [[Cumberland, Ohio]]. A material or weld defect was the cause.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://primis.phmsa.dot.gov/comm/reports/operator/OperatorIM_opid_19160.html |title=PHMSA: Stakeholder Communications |publisher=DOT.gov |accessdate=April 2, 2013 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009022828/http://primis.phmsa.dot.gov/comm/reports/operator/OperatorIM_opid_19160.html |archivedate=October 9, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=CPF No. 3-2011-1018H |url=http://primis.phmsa.dot.gov/comm/reports/enforce/documents/320111018H/320111018H_CAO_11172011_text.pdf |accessdate=28 November 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161225125813/http://primis.phmsa.dot.gov/comm/reports/enforce/documents/320111018H/320111018H_CAO_11172011_text.pdf |archivedate=December 25, 2016 }}</ref> * Early on March 17, a 20-inch steel [[CenterPoint Energy]] natural gas line running through a [[Minneapolis, Minnesota]] neighborhood ruptured, and gas from it ignited, caused evacuations to buildings nearby, and Interstate 35W was closed from downtown Minneapolis to Highway 62. There were no injuries. The Minnesota Office of Pipeline Safety later found the pipe there was not designed to handle the load of soil and passing cars, and efforts to shore up the pipeline were incorrectly carried out.<ref name="dot7">{{cite web|url=http://primis.phmsa.dot.gov/comm/reports/operator/OperatorIM_opid_12350.html?nocache=5865#_Incidents_tab_3 |publisher=primis.phmsa.dot.gov |title=PHMSA: Stakeholder Communications – Operator Information |accessdate=October 5, 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005110154/http://primis.phmsa.dot.gov/comm/reports/operator/OperatorIM_opid_12350.html?nocache=5865 |archivedate=October 5, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=David Joles |url=http://www.startribune.com/local/118164804.html |title=Light 'like the sun' rose above Mpls. blast crater |publisher=StarTribune.com |accessdate=April 2, 2013 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130825235202/http://www.startribune.com/local/118164804.html |archivedate=August 25, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://southwestminneapolis.patch.com/articles/report-id-s-cause-of-windom-pipeline-explosion |title=Report ID's Cause of Windom Pipeline Explosion |work=Southwest Minneapolis, Minnesota Patch |accessdate=January 15, 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130429075734/http://southwestminneapolis.patch.com/articles/report-id-s-cause-of-windom-pipeline-explosion |archivedate=April 29, 2013 }}</ref> * A farmer and rancher near [[White Oak Township, Michigan]] smelled gasoline on April 13, and discovered gasoline from a products pipeline leaking into a drainage ditch. As of late September, an estimated 460,000 gallons of gasoline had been released, with about 111,000 gallons of it recovered.<ref>{{cite web|title=Company Continues Probe into Mid-Michigan Gas Leak |url=http://www.wilx.com/home/headlines/Company_Continues_Probe_into_Mid-Michigan_Gas_Leak_121624444.html |website=archive.is |accessdate=28 November 2016 |date=28 November 2016 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20161128011004/http://www.wilx.com/home/headlines/Company_Continues_Probe_into_Mid-Michigan_Gas_Leak_121624444.html |archivedate=November 28, 2016 |df= }}</ref> * On May 7, a threaded connection failed on a [[Keystone Pipeline]] pump at a station in [[Sargent County, North Dakota]], spilling about 400 barrels of crude oil. Due to a number of other leaks on this pipeline system, Keystone's owner, [[TransCanada Corporation]], was given a Corrective Action Order by PHMSA.<ref>{{cite web|title=CPF No. 3-2011-5006H |url=http://primis.phmsa.dot.gov/comm/reports/enforce/documents/320115006H/320115006H_Amended%20CAO_06282011_text.pdf |accessdate=28 November 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170209062725/https://primis.phmsa.dot.gov/comm/reports/enforce/documents/320115006H/320115006H_Amended%20CAO_06282011_text.pdf |archivedate=February 9, 2017 }}</ref> * An 8-inch NGL pipeline failed in [[Romeoville, Illinois]] on May 14, leaking about 4200 gallons of butane. Corrosion inside a casing under a road was the cause of the failure. Corrosion only 2.5 feet from the failure had been seen by a smart pig run in 2007, but was not within action limits at the time.<ref>{{cite web|title=CPF No. 3-2011-5008S |url=http://primis.phmsa.dot.gov/comm/reports/enforce/documents/320115008S/320115008S_Notice%20of%20Proposed%20Safety%20Order_06152011_text.pdf |accessdate=28 November 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216044534/https://primis.phmsa.dot.gov/comm/reports/enforce/documents/320115008S/320115008S_Notice%20of%20Proposed%20Safety%20Order_06152011_text.pdf |archivedate=February 16, 2017 }}</ref> * On May 19, a 10-inch crude oil pipeline ruptured near [[Maysville, Oklahoma]]. Over {{convert|42,000|USgal|L}} of crude were lost. There was no fire. Internal pipeline corrosion was the cause.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2011/01/20/pipeline-outage-sunoco-oklahoma-idUKN2014891220110120 |agency=Reuters |first=Janet |last=McGurty |title=UPDATE 2-Sunoco shuts Oklahoma crude line after Weds. leak |date=January 20, 2011 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018191659/http://uk.reuters.com/article/2011/01/20/pipeline-outage-sunoco-oklahoma-idUKN2014891220110120 |archivedate=October 18, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://primis.phmsa.dot.gov/comm/reports/operator/OperatorIM_opid_18718.html?nocache=5913#_Incidents_tab_4 |title=PHMSA: Stakeholder Communications |website=Primis.phmsa.dot.gov |accessdate=January 15, 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141022133300/http://primis.phmsa.dot.gov/comm/reports/operator/OperatorIM_opid_18718.html?nocache=5913 |archivedate=October 22, 2014 }}</ref> * A 2-inch lateral on a crude oil pipeline rupture in [[Huntington Beach, California]] on July 1. A major road, Goldenwest Street, had to be closed for cleaning and pipeline repairs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ktla.com/news/landing/ktla-southwest-oil-leak,0,7386337.story |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 14, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902094232/http://www.ktla.com/news/landing/ktla-southwest-oil-leak%2C0%2C7386337.story |archivedate=September 2, 2012 |df= }}</ref> * Late on July 1, a 12-inch Exxon Mobil crude oil pipeline. also known as the Silvertip Pipeline, ruptured, and spilled about 63,000 gallons of oil into the [[Yellowstone River]] in south-central Montana. There was confusion in the pipeline control room, causing a delayed pipeline shutdown. Some residents of [[Laurel, Montana]] had to be evacuated.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/03/us/03oilspill.html |work=The New York Times |first=Anahad |last=O'Connor |title=Ruptured Pipeline Spills Oil Into Yellowstone River |date=July 2, 2011 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151010045055/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/03/us/03oilspill.html |archivedate=October 10, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ktvq.com/news/laurel-residents-evacuate-after-oil-pipeline-break/ |title=Laurel residents evacuate after oil pipeline break |work=KTVQ.com |accessdate=January 15, 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026211809/http://www.ktvq.com/news/laurel-residents-evacuate-after-oil-pipeline-break/ |archivedate=October 26, 2014}}</ref> The break near Billings fouled the riverbank and forced municipalities and irrigation districts to close intakes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2011/07/03/exxon-oil-spill-in-montana-river-prompts-evacuations/#ixzz1R8GNIrB2 |work=Fox News |title=Exxon Oil Spill in Montana River Prompts Evacuations |date=July 3, 2011 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111222143109/http://www.foxnews.com/us/2011/07/03/exxon-oil-spill-in-montana-river-prompts-evacuations/ |archivedate=December 22, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/exxon-oil-spill-prompts-evacuations/2011/07/03/AGm8UQwH_video.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121112172648/http://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/exxon-oil-spill-prompts-evacuations/2011/07/03/AGm8UQwH_video.html | dead-url=yes | archive-date=November 12, 2012 | work=The Washington Post |date=July 3, 2011 |title=Exxon oil spill prompts evacuations}}</ref> Exxon later increased the spill size estimate to 1500 barrels in January 2012 after seeing the damage to the pipeline.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/greenspace/2011/07/exxon-pipeline-spill-on-yellowstone-river.html |work=Los Angeles Times |title=Greenspace |date=July 3, 2011 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104125051/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/greenspace/2011/07/exxon-pipeline-spill-on-yellowstone-river.html |archivedate=November 4, 2012 }}</ref> About 140 people were evacuated starting about 12:15&nbsp;a.m. Saturday due to concerns about possible explosions and the overpowering fumes. All were allowed to return after instruments showed petroleum odors had decreased,<ref name="msnbc.msn.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/43619388/ns/us_news-environment/ |title=ExxonMobil pipe spills oil into Yellowstone River |work=msnbc.com |accessdate=January 19, 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105123050/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/43619388/ns/us_news-environment/ |archivedate=November 5, 2012 }}</ref> although no information was available regarding the concentrations of benzene in air. Speculation involves high water flow in the Yellowstone River may have scoured the river bed and exposed the pipe. Consequently, with three oil refineries are located in the Billings area, the fire chief for the city of Laurel said he asked all three to turn off the flow of oil in their pipelines under the river after the leak was reported. Exxon Mobil and Cenex Harvest Refinery did so, and Conoco Phillips said that its pipe was already shutdown.<ref name="msnbc.msn.com" /> Cenex had a release into the Yellowstone River in September 2002. Exxon Mobil later announced the cleanup would cost $135&nbsp;million. In 2015, Exxon Mobil was fined $1&nbsp;million by PHMSA for this incident.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2012/01/19/exxon-yellowstone-spill-1500-barrels-not-1000/ |work=Fox News |title=Exxon: Yellowstone spill 1,500 barrels, not 1,000 |date=January 19, 2012 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208091909/http://www.foxnews.com/us/2012/01/19/exxon-yellowstone-spill-1500-barrels-not-1000/ |archivedate=February 8, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/business/energy/20130914-lawsuits-against-exxon-mobil-mount-over-big-oil-pipeline-spills.ece |title=Lawsuits against Exxon Mobil mount over big oil pipeline spills |publisher= |accessdate=January 15, 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021015804/http://www.dallasnews.com/business/energy/20130914-lawsuits-against-exxon-mobil-mount-over-big-oil-pipeline-spills.ece |archivedate=October 21, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deq.mt.gov/statesuperfund/silvertipoilspill/default.mcpx |title=Montana DEQ – Page Not Found |publisher= |accessdate=January 15, 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128163142/http://deq.mt.gov/StateSuperfund/silvertipoilspill/default.mcpx |archivedate=January 28, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyinterlake.com/news/state_news/exxon-mobil-gets-million-penalty-for-pipeline-spill/article_199baf3c-a380-11e4-9674-d3ebafa41c24.html |title=Exxon Mobil gets $1 million penalty for pipeline spill |work=Daily Inter Lake |accessdate=January 18, 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128004826/http://www.dailyinterlake.com/news/state_news/exxon-mobil-gets-million-penalty-for-pipeline-spill/article_199baf3c-a380-11e4-9674-d3ebafa41c24.html |archivedate=January 28, 2015 }}</ref> * On July 20, a six-month-old, 30-inch natural gas pipeline exploded near [[Gillette, Wyoming]], creating a {{convert|60|ft|m|adj=on}} crater. There was no fire, nor any injuries. Construction or installation issues caused the failure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upi.com/Business_News/2011/07/24/Wyoming-nat-gas-pipeline-out-of-commission/UPI-87131311487780/ |title=Wyoming nat gas pipeline out of commission |work=UPI |accessdate=January 15, 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203115900/http://www.upi.com/Business_News/2011/07/24/Wyoming-nat-gas-pipeline-out-of-commission/UPI-87131311487780/ |archivedate=February 3, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/story/2012/10/24/transcanada-pipelines-bison-explosion.html |title=Quality concerns arose before TransCanada pipeline blast |work=CBC News |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025044617/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/story/2012/10/24/transcanada-pipelines-bison-explosion.html |archivedate=October 25, 2012 }}</ref> * A pipeline carrying jet fuel ruptured in [[Mango, Florida]] on July 22. About {{convert|31,500|USgal|L}} of fuel spilled. There was no fire or injuries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://brandon.patch.com/articles/officials-probe-leak-of-31500-gallons-of-jet-fuel-near-mango-cleanup-ongoing |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 14, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328041114/http://brandon.patch.com/articles/officials-probe-leak-of-31500-gallons-of-jet-fuel-near-mango-cleanup-ongoing |archivedate=March 28, 2012}}</ref> * On August 13, an 8-inch NGL pipeline ruptured near [[Onawa, Iowa]] at a Missouri River crossing, during flooding conditions. About 818 barrels of Natural Gasoline was lost. There were no evacuations or injuries, but two other pipelines in the same right of way were forced to shut down.<ref>{{cite web|title=CPF No. 3-2011-5010H |url=http://primis.phmsa.dot.gov/comm/reports/enforce/documents/320115010H/320115010H_CAO_09162011.pdf |accessdate=28 November 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211093221/https://primis.phmsa.dot.gov/Comm/reports/enforce/documents/320115010H/320115010H_CAO_09162011.pdf |archivedate=February 11, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=CPF No. 3011-5009H |url=http://primis.phmsa.dot.gov/comm/reports/enforce/documents/320115009H/320115009H_CAO_08192011.pdf |accessdate=28 November 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161225085315/http://primis.phmsa.dot.gov/comm/reports/enforce/documents/320115009H/320115009H_CAO_08192011.pdf |archivedate=December 25, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wowt.com/home/headlines/Gas_Leaking_Into_Missouri_River_From_Pipeline_127693933.html|title=Pipeline Leak Sends Gasoline Into Missouri River|agency=Associated Press|publisher=|accessdate=January 15, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/2012/May/12-enrd-679.html |title=Mid-Americ