{{Material-stub}}

'''Matchboard''' by definition is "a board with a groove cut along one edge and a tongue along the other so as to fit snugly with the edges of similarly cut boards."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/matchboard|title=Definition of MATCHBOARD|website=www.merriam-webster.com|language=en|access-date=2017-09-21}}</ref>
[[File:Bramble Cottage, Lundy (1).jpg|thumb|Bramble Cottage on [[Lundy Island]], weathered cedar matchboarding in an exposed location]] Matchboarding can be used both internally and externally, and can be layered in many different styles including: square edge, feather edge, [[Shiplap|ship lap]] and [[tongue and groove]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wooduchoose.com/w.cfm/wooden/tongue-and-groove/|title=Tongue and groove Boarding {{!}} Tongue and groove panelling {{!}} Wood panelling {{!}} T&G Boards|website=Wooduchoose - the wood price comparison website|language=en|access-date=2017-09-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timbersource.co.uk/services/cladding|title=Timber Cladding for interior & exterior use {{!}} Timbersource|website=www.timbersource.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-09-21}}</ref>
Matchboard was most popular in the late [[Victorian era|Victorian period]], when woodworking machinery had developed that could cut the edge joints quickly and cheaply. In the 1930s, further developments in glues and veneer-cutting machinery made [[plywood]] affordable. This also gave a cleanly smooth-surfaced [[Modernism|Modernist]] look that suited the taste for new styles. Matchboard then became much less popular. In the 1970s there was a resurgence of interest in the style as a [[Retro style|retro]] feature, but this was usually provided, for cost reasons, as a faux matchboard effect pressed into the surface of a plywood board.
