'''Nordic Windpower''' was a privately owned manufacturer of [[wind turbines]] based in [[Kansas City, Missouri]] in the [[United States]]. Nordic Windpower filed for liquidation in the Kansas City Bankruptcy court in October 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/kansascity/print-edition/2012/10/19/turbine-maker-nordic-windpower-files.html |title=Nordic files |publisher=Kansas City BizJournal |date= |accessdate=2013-02-27}}</ref>
The company had roots in a Swedish government wind turbine research and development program started 1975. Early prototypes in this program were erected in [[Maglarp]], [[Skåne]] and [[Näsudden]], [[Gotland]]. Nordic Windpower's N1000 turbine was designed with inspiration from the Maglarp prototype and has [[Unconventional wind turbines#Wind turbines with two blades|two blades]] rather than the more conventional three.
In the 1990s the company became privately owned Nordic Windpower AB. After selling only 5 turbines it became a United States entity in 2005 and promptly sold 7 turbines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nordicwindpower.com/history.html |title=Nordic WindPower |publisher=Nordic WindPower |date= |accessdate=2010-12-22}}</ref><ref>http://www.nordicwindpower.com/images/2D_sidebar_1.jpg</ref> It received a $16 million loan guarantee from the [[United States Department of Energy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/business/ci_16913416?nclick_check=1 |title=Nordic Windpower leaving California - San Jose Mercury News |publisher=Mercurynews.com |date= |accessdate=2010-12-22}}</ref> Its private owners were [[Khosla Ventures]], [[New Enterprise Associates]] and Novus Energy Partners, [[Goldman Sachs]], [[Impax Asset Management Group|Impax Asset Management]], I2BF Venture Capital, Pulsar Energy Capital and other investors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nordicwindpower.com/investor.html |title=Nordic WindPower |publisher=Nordic WindPower |date= |accessdate=2010-12-22}}</ref>
Before moving to Kansas City it had its corporate headquarters in [[Berkeley, California]] with a production facility in [[Pocatello, Idaho]]. Engineering design was carried out in [[Bristol]], [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nordicwindpower.com/overview.html |title=Nordic WindPower |publisher=Nordic WindPower |date= |accessdate=2010-12-22}}</ref> In December 2010 Nordic announced its plans to move to Missouri to be closer to its target market and was offered $5.6 million in conditional incentive packages to relocate to [[Kansas City International Airport]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2010/12/21/BUG81GU0KL.DTL |title=Berkeley's Nordic Windpower moving to Missouri |publisher=Sfgate.com |date= 2010-12-22|accessdate=2010-12-22 |first=David R. |last=Baker}}</ref> Nordic temporarily occupied {{convert|50000|sqft|m2}} of the {{convert|1700000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} former American Airlines Overhaul facility at the airport which the airline had abandoned. It was scheduled to be the first tenant at the [[KCI Intermodal Business Centre]] being developed by [[Trammell Crow Company]] at the airport.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kansascity.com/2010/12/21/2536178/turbine-maker-coming-to-kc.html |title=Turbine maker coming to KC |publisher=KansasCity.com |date= |accessdate=2010-12-22}}</ref>
